This article is an executive order issued by President Barack Obama on December 11, 2009. The order states that all executive branch departments and agencies of the Federal Government will be closed and their employees excused from duty for the last half of the scheduled workday on Thursday, December 24, 2009, the day before Christmas Day. However, certain offices and installations, as determined by the heads of executive branch departments and agencies, may remain open and certain employees may be required to work for reasons of national security, defense, or other public need. The order also states that December 24, 2009, will be considered as falling within the scope of previous executive orders and statutes regarding the pay and leave of employees of the United States. It clarifies that the order does not create any rights or benefits enforceable by any party against the United States or its entities.